label("$y$",(6.5,-2.5),SE);
label("$z$",(7.5,-2.5),SE);
label("$g$",(6,-.5),SW);
[/asy]
To maximize $+x+y+z-g$, we want to maximize $x$, $y$, and $z$ while minimizing $g$. First, we find the critical points of the function $f(x,y,z,g) = x+y+z-g$ by setting the partial derivatives equal to zero:

$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = 1 = 0$$
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = 1 = 0$$
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial z} = 1 = 0$$
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial g} = -1 = 0$$

Since none of these equations have solutions, there are no critical points. Next, we evaluate the function at each vertex of the feasible region:

$$f(3,4,5,7) = 9$$
$$f(3,4,5,8) = 10$$
$$f(3,4,6,7) = 10$$
$$f(4,4,5,6) = 9$$

Therefore, the maximum possible value of $+x+y+z-g$ is $\boxed{10}$.

Find the characteristic polynomial of the following matrix:
$\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{25}{3} & -\frac{43}{6} \\
\frac{43}{6} & \frac{5}{3} \\
\end{array}
\right)$
The characteristic polynomial of a matrix is a polynomial whose roots are the eigenvalues of the matrix. To find the characteristic polynomial, we can use the formula:

$$p(x) = \det(A - xI)$$

where A is the given matrix, x is an indeterminate, I is the identity matrix, and det denotes the determinant.

Substituting the given matrix into the formula, we get:

$$p(x) = \det\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{25}{3} - x & -\frac{43}{6} \\
\frac{43}{6} & \frac{5}{3} - x \\
\end{array}
\right)$$

Expanding the determinant, we get:

$$p(x) = \left(-\frac{25}{3} - x\right)\left(\frac{5}{3} - x\right) - \left(-\frac{43}{6}\right)\left(\frac{43}{6}\right)$$

Simplifying, we get:

$$p(x) = \left(-\frac{25}{3} - x\right)\left(\frac{5}{3} - x\right)

